(3622, 8, 2, 'Ngozi wants to sew a shirt and design its edges. Which stitch should she add last?', 'Hem stitch', 'Decorative stitch', 'Tack stitch', 'Basting stitch', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3623, 8, 2, 'A tacking stitch was added to hold the cloth while sewing. What should happen to it after the permanent stitch is added?', 'It should be coloured', 'It should be decorated', 'It should be removed', 'It should be tightened', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3624, 8, 2, 'What does a permanent stitch do that a temporary stitch cannot?', 'Stay in the fabric even after washing', 'Help you choose cloth colour', 'Remove wrinkles from the cloth', 'Mark the sewing lines', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3625, 8, 2, 'Which stitch is best when making table runners and tray covers look attractive?', 'Tack stitch', 'Hem stitch', 'Decorative stitch', 'Strength stitch', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3626, 8, 2, 'After sewing her dress, Aisha added flowers with coloured threads. What stitch was she likely using?', 'Running stitch', 'Chain stitch', 'Tacking stitch', 'Decorative stitch', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3627, 8, 2, 'What should you do after using a temporary stitch?', 'Colour over it', 'Cut the cloth edges', 'Remove it once the permanent stitch is added', 'Leave it to show beauty', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3628, 8, 2, 'Which situation is best for using a tacking stitch?', 'Cleaning the finished cloth', 'Holding parts of fabric in place for final sewing', 'Designing the cloth with flowers', 'Packing finished dresses', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3629, 8, 2, 'Tade made pillowcases using back stitches. What kind of stitch did he use?', 'Decorative stitch', 'Tacking stitch', 'Permanent stitch', 'Loose stitch', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3630, 8, 2, 'Uduak wants to sew a gift bag and add bright thread at the edge for design. What stitch fits best?', 'Tack stitch', 'Chain stitch', 'Buttonhole stitch', 'Decorative stitch', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3631, 8, 2, 'After sewing a seam, what is the next step to make it neat and flat?', 'Iron the seam properly', 'Wash the cloth quickly', 'Rub the seam with chalk', 'Colour it with a pen', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3632, 8, 2, 'If you want to sew a seam that hides the raw edges completely, what should you use?', 'Double stitch', 'French seam', 'Base seam', 'Top seam', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3633, 8, 2, 'Tolu wants to sew her blouse neatly with a strong finish. What seam would be most suitable?', 'Run and fell seam', 'Loose stitch seam', 'Fancy seam', 'Buttonhole seam', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3634, 8, 2, 'Before making a plain seam, which is most important?', 'Washing your hands', 'Preparing paper for drawing', 'Measuring and marking the fabric', 'Asking your classmate for help', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3635, 8, 2, 'Emeka used run and fell seam on his school bag. What is a good reason for his choice?', 'It is very stretchy and soft', 'It looks colorful from the outside', 'It is only for decoration', 'It makes the seam strong and durable', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3636, 8, 2, 'What makes the French seam suitable for thin or transparent fabrics?', 'It adds extra designs', 'It covers the raw edges completely', 'It makes sewing faster', 'It uses bright thread', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3637, 8, 2, 'When making seams on brown paper for practice, what skill are you building?', 'How to design party clothes', 'The right way to cut hairlines', 'How to sew straight and even seams', 'The art of folding wrappers', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3638, 8, 2, 'Why must we backstitch at the beginning and end of a seam?', 'To show the cloth belongs to someone', 'To make sure the seam does not come undone', 'To leave space for folding', 'To change the colour of the thread', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3639, 8, 2, 'If a learner wants to display different seam types in class, what can they do?', 'Draw pictures of the seams', 'Produce an album showing the steps', 'Talk about them only from memory', 'Buy a ready-made cloth from the market', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3640, 8, 2, 'A student cuts two equal pieces of brown paper and sews a French seam. What did she demonstrate?', 'Use of factory tools', 'Fabric washing', 'Seam-making process', 'Ironing method', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 0, '2025-07-17 10:15:10'),
(3641, 8, 3, 'Emeka has a set of tools but doesnt know how to use them. What would you advise him to do first?', 'Learn their names and uses from a trusted adult or book', 'Give them to someone who likes sewing more than him', 'Use them for drawing since they are sharp', 'Keep them until someone teaches him in the future', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3642, 8, 3, 'Which is the best way to care for sharp tools like scissors?', 'Cover them with fabric so they dont hurt anyone', 'Let a friend borrow them if they promise to return', 'Store them safely and wipe them clean after each use', 'Leave them near your sewing space for quick access', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3643, 8, 3, 'A school is teaching students to make articles by hand. Which activity will best support this?', 'Learning to sew simple stitches step by step', 'Reading a story about tailors and designers', 'Visiting a fashion shop to look at finished clothes', 'Watching a movie about sewing machines', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3644, 8, 3, 'Which of these is most useful when creating neat and safe sewing projects?', 'Keeping your tools clean, stored properly, and using them correctly', 'Using your tools only when an adult is watching', 'Sewing as fast as you can to finish early', 'Choosing tools based on how colorful they are', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3645, 8, 3, 'Two learners made headbands. One used the right tools, the other didnt. What would likely happen?', 'The headband made without tools may last longer', 'The one with the correct tools is more likely to make a better-quality headband', 'Both will have similar results because sewing is easy', 'The one with the wrong tools may be more creative', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3646, 8, 3, 'How can we best encourage young children to enjoy sewing?', 'Make them copy the work of older students every time', 'Only show them sewing on a chalkboard', 'Allow them to explore with safe tools and kind guidance', 'Give them complex tools so they feel like experts', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3647, 8, 3, 'Which statement shows understanding of sewing tools?', 'I dont need to know their names to use them.', 'All sewing tools are the same and can be used anyhow.', 'I can sew with anything, even a pencil or stick.', 'Each tool has a purpose and should be used the right way.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3648, 8, 3, 'A student wants to make a design on a fabric that can be easily changed. Which type of stitch should she avoid?', 'Temporary stitch', 'Decorative stitch', 'Tack stitch', 'Permanent stitch', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3649, 8, 3, 'During practice, Ahmed used a decorative stitch to join pieces of fabric. His work kept coming apart. What did he do wrong?', 'He didnt press the fabric', 'He used thread that was too long', 'He used a stitch thats meant for decoration, not strength', 'He used plain coloured fabric', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3650, 8, 3, 'Which student showed a good understanding of stitches?', 'Chika said all stitches are for decoration only', 'Bolu used a tacking stitch before applying a back stitch', 'Sani used glue instead of stitching', 'Mariam stitched everything using only chains', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3651, 8, 3, 'Tolu says she prefers temporary stitches because they last forever. Whats the best response?', 'Temporary stitches are not strong and are usually removed later', 'They are colourful and beautiful', 'They are more expensive than other stitches', 'They are used in only machine work', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3652, 8, 3, 'Moyo wants to make a cloth cover that can be easily opened and closed. Which type of stitch should she avoid?', 'Temporary stitch', 'Chain stitch', 'Permanent stitch', 'Decorative stitch', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3653, 8, 3, 'After using a permanent stitch, what is the next thing to do with the temporary stitch?', 'Strengthen it', 'Colour it in', 'Leave it to become firm', 'Remove it carefully', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3654, 8, 3, 'A class assignment asked learners to make tray covers using stitches that beautify the edges. Which stitch would most likely be used?', 'Tack stitch', 'Base stitch', 'Chain stitch', 'Hem stitch', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3655, 8, 3, 'A teacher asks her pupils to create an album showing how to sew different seams. What is the purpose of this activity?', 'To help them learn the names of thread types', 'To make them decorate the cover of the book', 'To understand and remember the steps involved in making seams', 'To avoid using sewing machines at all', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3656, 8, 3, 'Mary says she used a French seam for her jeans. What is the likely problem with that choice?', 'It is too soft for rough fabrics like jeans', 'It is the best for jeans and trousers', 'It will make the cloth smell', 'It adds extra pockets', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3657, 8, 3, 'Sade made a bag and wants the seams to be strong and flat. What seam is the best option?', 'Fancy seam', 'Run and fell seam', 'French seam', 'Ribbon seam', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3658, 8, 3, 'Which action shows good understanding of seam construction?', 'Leaving the raw edges open for air', 'Using glue instead of thread', 'Avoiding paper practice', 'Measuring, sewing, and pressing each seam properly', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3659, 8, 3, 'After completing her project, Halima added labels showing the seam types. Why is this helpful?', 'It shows she understands the different seams used', 'It makes the cloth more colorful', 'It helps her classmates know the cloth price', 'It allows her to wash the seams properly', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3660, 8, 3, 'When making a seam album, what should be included?', 'The measurements only', 'Pictures of clothes from magazines', 'Step-by-step drawings or stitched samples', 'A list of fashion designers', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18'),
(3661, 8, 3, 'Uches seam keeps opening after sewing. What is a possible reason?', 'She used too much thread', 'She didnt press it enough', 'She used fancy buttons', 'She forgot to backstitch', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 0, '2025-07-17 10:20:18');
INSERT INTO `lessons` (`lesson_id`, `subject_id`, `class_id`, `lesson_number`, `title`, `description`, `vocabulary`, `content`, `thumbnail`, `video`, `updated_ on`) VALUES
(1, 1, 3, 'Lesson 1', 'Introduction/Components of Civic Education', 'This is an introductory lesson which will enable you to         understand the         basics of         this topic and the subject at whole', NULL, '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MMAaD7NeKxA', '2025-05-04 11:54:21'),
(2, 2, 4, 'Lesson 1', 'Meaning and Importance of Good Governance', 'Big Question: How do lines and shapes help us express our ideas in drawing?\n\n\r\nLearning Objectives:\n\r\n1. Understand the basic elements of drawing, including lines and shapes.\n\r\n2. Identify different types of lines (horizontal, vertical, diagonal, curved, zigzag).\n\r\n3. Use lines and shapes to create expressive drawings.\n\r\n4. Develop creativity and observation skills through drawing exercises.', '<b>Line</b>: A mark with length and direction\n<b>Shape</b>: The outline of an object, like a square or circle\n<b>Texture</b>: How something feels or looks like it would feel\n<b>Pattern</b>: A design made by repeating shapes or lines\n<b>Contrast</b>: Differences in color, shape, or tone', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:29:29'),
(3, 3, 5, 'Lesson 1', 'National Consciousness - Loyalty', 'Big Question: What is loyalty and why is it important?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Students will be able to define loyalty and identify its significance in personal and national contexts.\n2. Students will analyze examples of loyalty and disloyalty through storytelling.\n3. Students will demonstrate understanding by participating in activities that reflect loyalty.', '<b>Loyalty</b>: Being faithful to someone or something\n<b>Nation</b>: A country or land where people share a common identity\n<b>Responsibility</b>: Being dependable and doing what you are expected to do\n<b>Honesty</b>: Telling the truth and being sincere\n<b>Courage</b>: Being brave enough to do what is right', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 23:03:29'),
(4, 2, 4, 'Lesson 2', 'Discovering the World of Arts and Craft', 'Big Question: How do we use tones to create beautiful artwork?\n\n\r\nLearning Objectives:\n\r\n1. Define tones and explain their role in creating light and dark areas in a drawing.\n\r\n2. Identify techniques such as hatching, cross-hatching, and shading.\n\r\n3. Apply these techniques to add depth and texture to drawings.\n\r\n4. Critique artworks to recognize how artists use tone effectively.', '<b>Tone</b>: The lightness or darkness of a color or area\n<b>Hatching</b>: Drawing closely spaced lines to create shading\n<b>Shading</b>: Darkening areas to show depth or shadow\n<b>Sketch</b>: A quick drawing\n<b>Volume</b>: The appearance of 3D form in a drawing', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:29:29'),
(5, 4, 5, 'Lesson 1', 'Discovering the World of Arts and Craft', 'Big Question: What makes arts and crafts important in our daily lives and culture?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Understand the role of arts and crafts in expressing cultural identity and emotions.\n2. Identify and use different materials to create art that tells a story.\n3. Develop critical thinking by comparing different art forms.\n4. Enhance creativity through hands-on art projects.', '<b>Art</b>: A form of creative expression through drawing, painting, and other visual media\n<b>Craft</b>: Handmade objects created with skill and creativity\n<b>Culture</b>: The customs and traditions of a group of people\n<b>Design</b>: A plan or drawing to show the look or function of something\n<b>Creativity</b>: Using imagination to make something new', '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ql9XcHgV4DE', '2025-05-25 22:38:18'),
(6, 6, 5, 'Lesson 1', 'British Rule of Nigeria', 'Big Question: Why did the British occupy Nigeria, and how did it impact the country?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Understand the reasons for British occupation of Nigeria.\n2. Describe the impact of British rule on different aspects of Nigerian society.\n3. Explore moral and ethical issues associated with colonialism.\n4. Develop critical thinking by evaluating different historical perspectives.', '<b>Colonialism</b>: Control of one country by another\n<b>Imperialism</b>: A policy of extending a countrys power and influence through colonization\n<b>British Rule</b>: The period when Nigeria was governed by Britain\n<b>Protectorate</b>: A region that is controlled and protected by another country\n<b>Resistance</b>: Opposition to something, especially injustice', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:39:22'),
(7, 7, 4, 'Lesson 1', 'What is Home Economics', 'Big Question: What makes a house a home?\n\n\r\nLearning Objectives:\n\r\n1. Understand the difference between a house and a home.\n\r\n2. Identify different types of houses and their features.\n\r\n3. Explain the functions of a home.\n\r\n4. Reflect on ways to create a comfortable and welcoming home environment.', '<b>House</b>: A building for people to live in\n<b>Home</b>: A place where people feel safe and cared for\n<b>Shelter</b>: A place that protects you from danger or bad weather\n<b>Family</b>: A group of people related by blood or love\n<b>Comfort</b>: A state of physical ease and happiness', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:29:39'),
(8, 8, 5, 'Lesson 1', 'The Family - Foundation of Society', '', '<b>Needs</b>: Basic things required to live, like food and shelter\n<b>Wants</b>: Things we desire but do not necessarily need\n<b>Priority</b>: Something important that needs to be done first\n<b>Budget</b>: A plan for how money will be spent\n<b>Savings</b>: Money kept for future use', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:40:10'),
(9, 10, 2, 'Lesson 1', 'The Scope of Social Studies', '', NULL, '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EplgbX-ALLM', '2025-05-04 11:53:03'),
(10, 11, 4, 'Lesson 1', 'Understanding Our Social Environment', 'Big Question: Who are we, and what makes us unique?\n\n\r\nLearning Objectives:\n\r\n1. Define identity and its components (name, tribe, religion, appearance).\n\r\n2. Appreciate differences and similarities among people.\n\r\n3. Create a personal identity poster.\n\r\n4. Practice empathy through classroom sharing activities.', '<b>Identity</b>: Who someone is, including name, family, and traits\n<b>Traits</b>: Characteristics or features of a person\n<b>Belonging</b>: Feeling accepted or included\n<b>Culture</b>: The beliefs and practices of a group of people\n<b>Tradition</b>: Customs or beliefs passed down over time', '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DXwV-jpBP-E', '2025-05-25 22:29:48'),
(11, 13, 3, 'Lesson 1', 'The Nuclear and Extended Families', '', NULL, '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TuBZI-E5AS8', '2025-05-04 11:55:21'),
(12, 12, 5, 'Lesson 1', 'Man and his Environment', 'Big Question: How does our environment shape who we are, and how do we shape our environment?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Describe how their environment influences their daily lives.\n2. Explain how their actions can impact the environment.\n3. Identify ways to positively contribute to their environment.\n4. Reflect on the importance of maintaining a clean and healthy environment.', '<b>Environment</b>: The surroundings where people, animals, and plants live\n<b>Pollution</b>: Making the environment dirty or unsafe\n<b>Waste</b>: Things that are thrown away because they are no longer useful\n<b>Cleanliness</b>: Being free from dirt and germs\n<b>Recycling</b>: Turning waste materials into new products', '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nQfRZPDuOpY', '2025-05-25 22:42:28'),
(13, 14, 1, 'Lesson 1', '', '', NULL, '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RfdkGuGJ0Yo', '2025-05-04 11:53:44'),
(14, 15, 1, 'Lesson 1', 'Respect: The Key to Building a Great Nation', '', NULL, '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1_JU5rVj9IQ', '2025-05-04 11:52:47'),
(15, 16, 2, 'Lesson 1', 'What is Civic Education', '', NULL, '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vGc1-S9iI2U', '2025-05-04 11:52:34'),
(16, 3, 5, 'Lesson 2', '', 'Big Question: What makes a good leader?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Understand the concept of governance and different types of leadership.\n2. Identify characteristics of good leadership.\n3. Apply the knowledge of leadership types to solve group problems.\n4. Demonstrate the ability to choose appropriate leadership styles in different situations.', '<b>Leadership</b>: The act of guiding and directing others\n<b>Governance</b>: The way a group or country is managed\n<b>Influence</b>: The power to affect how others think or act\n<b>Decision</b>: A choice made after thinking about different options\n<b>Example</b>: A model or pattern that others can follow', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:34:29'),
(17, 3, 5, 'Lesson 3', '', 'Big Question: How does leadership affect our lives?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Analyze real-life examples of good and bad leadership.\n2. Reflect on how leadership decisions shape communities.\n3. Apply leadership concepts to solve classroom or home-based problems.', '<b>Leader</b>: A person who guides or shows others the way\n<b>Power</b>: The ability to control or influence others\n<b>Respect</b>: Treating people with care and honour\n<b>Role</b>: A part played by a person in a group or situation\n<b>Authority</b>: The right to give orders and make decisions', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:34:29'),
(18, 3, 5, 'Lesson 4', '', 'Big Question: Why do we need different arms of government?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Understand the roles of the Executive, Legislative, and Judiciary arms of government.\n2. Explain why having separate arms of government helps ensure fairness and justice.\n3. Identify how these roles mirror structures in their own school or community.\n4. Apply their understanding of checks and balances in a practical scenario.', '<b>Government</b>: A group of people who make and enforce laws\n<b>Executive</b>: The arm of government that carries out laws\n<b>Legislative</b>: The arm that makes laws\n<b>Judiciary</b>: The arm that interprets laws and ensures justice\n<b>Checks and Balances</b>: A system that prevents one part of government from becoming too powerful', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:34:29'),
(19, 3, 5, 'Lesson 5', '', 'Big Question: How do groups of people bring about change?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Define what a pressure group is and explain its purpose.\n2. Identify examples of pressure groups in Nigeria.\n3. Describe how pressure groups can influence change in a community.\n4. Discuss the challenges that pressure groups might face.', '<b>Pressure Group</b>: A group that tries to influence decisions or policies\n<b>Influence</b>: The power to change someones opinion or decision\n<b>Advocacy</b>: Public support for or recommendation of a cause\n<b>Protest</b>: A public demonstration of disagreement or demand for change\n<b>Democracy</b>: A system of government where people have the power to choose leaders', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:34:29'),
(20, 3, 5, 'Lesson 6', '', 'Big Question: Why is hard work important?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Understand the concept of hard work and its importance.\n2. Distinguish between hard work and laziness.\n3. Recognize ways to encourage and discourage hard work.\n4. Reflect on how hard work leads to rewards and success.', '<b>Hard Work</b>: Putting in effort to complete tasks or reach goals\n<b>Laziness</b>: Unwillingness to work or use energy\n<b>Reward</b>: Something received in return for effort\n<b>Determination</b>: Not giving up despite difficulty\n<b>Success</b>: Achieving a goal or purpose', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:34:29'),
(21, 3, 5, 'Lesson 7', '', 'Big Question: What is social injustice, and why does it matter?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Understand the concept of social injustice and fairness.\n2. Identify examples of social injustice.\n3. Discuss ways to address unfair situations.\n4. Recognize the consequences of ignoring social injustices.', '<b>Justice</b>: Treating people fairly and equally\n<b>Fairness</b>: Making decisions without favouritism\n<b>Bias</b>: An unfair preference for or against something\n<b>Rights</b>: Things that people are allowed to do or have\n<b>Responsibility</b>: Duties we must perform to ensure fairness', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:34:29'),
(22, 3, 5, 'Lesson 8', '', 'Big Question: How can we all contribute to a better society?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Reflect on key values: loyalty, leadership, hard work, and justice.\n2. Identify ways to apply these values in their community.\n3. Create a personal plan for contributing to a better society.\n4. Understand how their actions, no matter how small, can make a difference.', '<b>Value</b>: Something important or worthwhile\n<b>Community</b>: A group of people living in the same area\n<b>Respect</b>: Showing regard for others feelings and rights\n<b>Empathy</b>: Understanding and sharing someone elses feelings\n<b>Contribution</b>: Doing something that helps a group or cause', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:34:29'),
(23, 12, 5, 'Lesson 2', '', 'Big Question: What makes a family, and why is it important to understand the roles of everyone in it?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Identify the different roles within a family.\n2. Understand the importance of each family members role.\n3. Demonstrate respect and responsibility toward family members.\n4. Analyze how tolerance and problem-solving contribute to family harmony.', '<b>Family</b>: A group of people related by blood, marriage, or care\n<b>Father</b>: A male parent\n<b>Mother</b>: A female parent\n<b>Siblings</b>: Brothers and sisters\n<b>Responsibility</b>: A duty or task that someone is expected to do', '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JRx4_I3H4CA', '2025-05-25 22:42:28'),
(24, 12, 5, 'Lesson 3', '', 'Big Question: How can we stay united even though we are all different?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Identify and understand the concepts of culture, diversity, and unity.\n2. Explore and appreciate different cultural traditions.\n3. Discuss and apply strategies for resolving conflicts and building empathy.\n4. Promote respect and inclusivity among peers through interactive activities.', '<b>Unity</b>: Living together in peace and harmony\n<b>Diversity</b>: Differences among people in culture, language, religion, etc.\n<b>Culture</b>: The way of life of a group of people\n<b>Tolerance</b>: Respecting people with different views or backgrounds\n<b>Conflict</b>: A disagreement or argument', '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rr8UrArQFUc', '2025-05-25 22:42:28'),
(25, 12, 5, 'Lesson 4', '', 'Big Question: What does it mean to be a responsible parent, and why is it important?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Understand the concept of responsible parenthood (love, care, honesty, patience, support).\n2. Recognize the impact of responsible parenting on family dynamics and individual growth.\n3. Reflect on personal contributions to support their parents and family.', '<b>Parenthood</b>: The state or role of being a parent\n<b>Love</b>: Deep affection or care for someone\n<b>Care</b>: Looking after someone or something\n<b>Patience</b>: Staying calm without getting angry or upset\n<b>Support</b>: Helping and encouraging someone', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:42:28'),
(26, 12, 5, 'Lesson 5', '', 'Big Question: How do we take care of our bodies as we grow?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Identify the physical changes that occur during pre-adolescence.\n2. Explain the importance of personal hygiene and its role in overall health.\n3. Develop a personal hygiene checklist and strategies for managing physical changes.\n4. Reflect on how to handle changes in body care and discuss common hygiene issues.', '<b>Body</b>: The physical structure of a person\n<b>Hygiene</b>: Practices that help maintain cleanliness and health\n<b>Adolescence</b>: The stage of growing from a child to an adult\n<b>Puberty</b>: Changes in the body during adolescence\n<b>Personal Care</b>: Taking care of your bodys cleanliness and appearance', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:42:28'),
(27, 12, 5, 'Lesson 6', '', 'Big Question: What does it mean to be a responsible citizen?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Understand the concept of responsible citizenship and its importance.\n2. Recognize the value of cultural diversity and the role of respect in a community.\n3. Identify ways to actively contribute to and improve ones community.\n4. Practice empathy and develop problem-solving skills for community issues.', '<b>Citizen</b>: A person who belongs to a country and has rights and responsibilities\n<b>Responsibility</b>: Something a person is expected to do\n<b>Right</b>: Something a person is allowed to have or do\n<b>Obedience</b>: Following rules and laws\n<b>Contribution</b>: Doing something to help your community', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:42:28'),
(28, 9, 5, 'Lesson 1', '', 'Big Question: What is personal security, and why is it important?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Understand the concept of personal security and its importance.\n2. Identify actions that support personal security.\n3. Explain why making safe choices is crucial.\n4. Demonstrate the ability to apply personal security concepts to real-life scenarios.', '<b>Personal Security</b>: Keeping yourself safe from danger or harm\n<b>Safety</b>: Being free from danger or risk\n<b>Awareness</b>: Knowing what is happening around you\n<b>Precaution</b>: Something done to prevent harm\n<b>Emergency</b>: A sudden situation that requires quick action', '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uUbhULS-8IA', '2025-05-25 22:40:35'),
(29, 9, 5, 'Lesson 2', '', 'Big Question: How can we stay safe from strangers?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Identify who strangers are and why caution is important.\n2. Understand and apply safety measures when encountering strangers.\n3. Analyze real-life scenarios to make safe choices.\n4. Discuss and reflect on personal safety strategies.', '<b>Stranger</b>: Someone you do not know or trust\n<b>Safety Rules</b>: Guidelines that help keep you safe\n<b>Body Boundaries</b>: Personal physical space that should be respected\n<b>Trusted Adult</b>: Someone you can go to when you feel unsafe\n<b>Abduction</b>: Being taken away by someone against your will', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:40:35'),
(30, 9, 5, 'Lesson 3', '', 'Big Question: Why should we be cautious about the food we eat and the products we use?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Identify unsafe foods, chemicals, and fake drugs.\n2. Understand the importance of checking labels, expiry dates, and purchasing from trusted sources.\n3. Apply critical thinking to make informed decisions about product safety.', '<b>Fake Drug</b>: A medicine that is not real or safe to use\n<b>Expired Product</b>: An item that is past its safe usage date\n<b>Label</b>: Information written on a product package\n<b>Safety Symbol</b>: A sign that warns or guides you for safety\n<b>Counterfeit</b>: Something made to look real but is fake', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:40:35'),
(31, 9, 5, 'Lesson 4', '', 'Big Question: What are our responsibilities to ensure our own safety and the safety of others?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Understand safe and unsafe behaviors in various situations.\n2. Apply critical thinking to real-life security scenarios.\n3. Demonstrate responsibility for their own safety and the safety of others.', '<b>Safe Choice</b>: A decision that helps avoid danger or harm\n<b>Unsafe Behaviour</b>: Actions that put you or others at risk\n<b>Risk</b>: The chance of something bad happening\n<b>Consequence</b>: What happens because of a choice or action\n<b>Responsibility</b>: Being accountable for your actions', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:40:35'),
(32, 9, 5, 'Lesson 5', '', '', '<b>Security Tips</b>: Helpful advice for staying safe\n<b>Role Model</b>: A person whose behaviour sets a good example\n<b>Real-Life Scenario</b>: A situation that happens in everyday life\n<b>Self-Defense</b>: Protecting yourself from harm\n<b>Awareness</b>: Being alert to what is happening around you', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:41:31'),
(33, 6, 5, 'Lesson 12', '', '', '<b>Slave Trade</b>: The buying and selling of people as slaves\n<b>Slavery</b>: A system where people are treated as property\n<b>Freedom</b>: The right to live without being controlled\n<b>Abolition</b>: The act of ending slavery\n<b>Resistance</b>: Fighting against unfair treatment', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:39:23'),
(34, 6, 5, 'Lesson 2', '', 'Big Question: What is nationalism, and why was it crucial for Nigerias independence?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Understand the concept of nationalism and its significance in Nigerias history.\n2. Identify key figures in the Nigerian nationalist movement.\n3. Recognize the impact of nationalism on Nigerias quest for independence.\n4. Discuss moral dilemmas related to nationalist methods and reflect on contemporary relevance.', '<b>Nationalism</b>: Love and loyalty to ones country with the desire for independence\n<b>Independence</b>: Freedom from control by another country\n<b>Self-Government</b>: A system where people rule themselves\n<b>Protest</b>: An action showing objection to something\n<b>Colony</b>: A country or area ruled by another country', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:39:23'),
(35, 6, 5, 'Lesson 3', '', 'Big Question: How did Herbert Macaulays actions shape Nigerias path to independence?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Understand Herbert Macaulays key contributions.\n2. Identify pivotal events in his life.\n3. Reflect on moral lessons from his leadership and apply them to modern contexts.', '<b>Herbert Macaulay</b>: A Nigerian nationalist known for his role in fighting colonial rule\n<b>Activist</b>: A person who works to bring about change\n<b>Freedom</b>: The right to act or speak without being stopped unfairly\n<b>Campaign</b>: Organized actions to achieve a goal\n<b>Newspaper</b>: Printed material used to inform people and spread ideas', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:39:23'),
(36, 6, 5, 'Lesson 4', '', 'Big Question: What role did Nnamdi Azikiwe play in Nigerias fight for independence?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Understand Azikiwes contributions to Nigerias independence movement.\n2. Identify challenges he faced and how he overcame them.\n3. Reflect on the importance of education and perseverance.', '<b>Nnamdi Azikiwe</b>: Nigerias first president and a key nationalist leader\n<b>Education</b>: The process of gaining knowledge\n<b>Leader</b>: A person who guides or directs others\n<b>Voice</b>: The ability to speak out and be heard\n<b>Democracy</b>: A system where citizens vote to choose leaders', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:39:23'),
(37, 6, 5, 'Lesson 5', '', 'Big Question: How did Obafemi Awolowos vision transform Nigeria?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Describe Awolowos early life and achievements.\n2. Understand how his vision contributed to national development.\n3. Reflect on the power of clear vision and hard work.', '<b>Obafemi Awolowo</b>: A prominent Nigerian leader and nationalist\n<b>Vision</b>: A clear plan or idea for the future\n<b>Legacy</b>: Something handed down from a persons work or life\n<b>Development</b>: Growth and progress in society\n<b>Education</b>: Learning that helps people grow and succeed', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:39:23'),
(38, 6, 5, 'Lesson 6', '', 'Big Question: What made Alhaji Ahmadu Bello a key figure in Northern Nigerias history?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Identify Bellos achievements and contributions.\n2. Understand his impact on education and development.\n3. Discuss complexities of his leadership.', '<b>Ahmadu Bello</b>: A key leader from Northern Nigeria\n<b>Northern Region</b>: One of the three main regions in colonial Nigeria\n<b>Premier</b>: Head of government in a region\n<b>Unity</b>: Being together or joined as a whole\n<b>Community Service</b>: Helping people in ones local area', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:39:23'),
(39, 6, 5, 'Lesson 7', '', '', '<b>British Colonization</b>: The period when Britain controlled Nigeria\n<b>Trading Posts</b>: Places where trade between countries or groups took place\n<b>Missionary</b>: A person sent to spread religion and education\n<b>Exploration</b>: Traveling to learn about unknown areas\n<b>Royal Niger Company</b>: A British trading company that influenced Nigerias development', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:39:23'),
(40, 6, 5, 'Lesson 8', '', '', '<b>Amalgamation</b>: The joining of two or more parts into one\n<b>Lugard</b>: The British governor who joined Northern and Southern Nigeria in 1914\n<b>1914</b>: The year Nigeria was officially joined into one country\n<b>Indirect Rule</b>: A system of governing using traditional leaders under colonial authority\n<b>Governor-General</b>: The British representative who ruled Nigeria', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:39:23'),
(41, 6, 5, 'Lesson 9', '', '', '<b>Traditional Rulers</b>: Leaders in Nigerian communities based on customs\n<b>Chief</b>: A respected leader of a community\n<b>Oba</b>: A Yoruba king\n<b>Emir</b>: A traditional Muslim ruler\n<b>Igwe</b>: An Igbo traditional ruler', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:39:23'),
(42, 6, 5, 'Lesson 10', '', '', '<b>Community Leader</b>: A person who guides and supports their community\n<b>Wisdom</b>: Knowledge gained from experience\n<b>Custom</b>: Traditional practices passed down over time\n<b>Elders</b>: Older people respected for their experience\n<b>Responsibility</b>: A duty to take care of something or someone', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:39:23'),
(43, 6, 5, 'Lesson 11', '', 'Big Question: How do historical landmarks help us understand our past and shape our future?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Identify key historical features and sites in Nigeria.\n2. Explain their significance to Nigerian history and heritage.\n3. Develop critical thinking about balancing preservation with development.', '<b>Historical Site</b>: A place important because of events that happened there in the past\n<b>Monument</b>: A structure built to remember a person or event\n<b>Preservation</b>: Keeping something in good condition over time\n<b>Museum</b>: A place where historical objects are kept and displayed\n<b>Tourist</b>: A person who visits a place for pleasure or learning', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:39:23'),
(56, 4, 5, 'Lesson 2', '', 'Big Question: How can different types of drawings express various aspects of our world?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Identify and describe the three types of drawings: Nature, Still Life, and Life.\n2. Understand how each type of drawing expresses different aspects of the world.\n3. Develop basic drawing techniques, such as observation, shading, and capturing movement.\n4. Cultivate emotional intelligence, creativity, critical thinking, and problem-solving skills through drawing activities.', '<b>Drawing</b>: Making a picture using lines\n<b>Nature Drawing</b>: Drawing objects from the natural environment like leaves and animals\n<b>Still Life</b>: Drawing non-living arranged objects like fruits and bottles\n<b>Life Drawing</b>: Drawing people or animals in action or still positions\n<b>Observation</b>: Carefully looking at something to understand or draw it', '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AHP_M4qPdxg', '2025-05-25 22:38:18'),
(57, 4, 5, 'Lesson 3', '', 'Big Question: How can we make special cards to celebrate important occasions?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Understand the different types of cards and their uses.\n2. Identify and select appropriate materials for making cards.\n3. Create personalized cards for various occasions.\n4. Apply creativity, critical thinking, and problem-solving skills in card-making.\n5. Reflect on the emotional significance of giving and receiving handmade cards.', '<b>Card</b>: A decorated piece of paper given for a special occasion\n<b>Occasion</b>: A special event like a birthday or holiday\n<b>Greeting</b>: A message to say hello or express good wishes\n<b>Design</b>: A creative plan for how something will look\n<b>Personalized</b>: Made to fit someones taste or name', '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q6bmNIAJfBM', '2025-05-25 22:38:18'),
(58, 4, 5, 'Lesson 4', '', 'Big Question: What is weaving, and how can we create beautiful patterns with paper?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Define weaving and explain the basic concepts of warp and weft.\n2. Identify and describe three types of weaving techniques: plain, twill, and mat weaving.\n3. Create a simple woven mat using colored paper strips.\n4. Demonstrate critical thinking by evaluating different weaving techniques.\n5. Develop problem-solving skills through hands-on weaving activities.', '<b>Weaving</b>: Making fabric or patterns by crossing threads over and under\n<b>Strips</b>: Thin, long pieces of material like paper or cloth\n<b>Warp</b>: The vertical threads held in place while weaving\n<b>Weft</b>: The horizontal threads woven through the warp\n<b>Mat</b>: A flat piece of material woven for decoration or use', '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AtWzJSPUK3U', '2025-05-25 22:38:18'),
(59, 4, 5, 'Lesson 5', '', 'Big Question: How can mosaics tell a story or send a message?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Understand what mosaics are and how they are made.\n2. Identify different materials used in mosaics and their purposes.\n3. Create your own simple mosaic design to convey a message or story.\n4. Evaluate how your mosaic and others mosaics convey their intended messages.', '<b>Mosaic</b>: A picture or pattern made by sticking small pieces of materials like stone or paper\n<b>Tile</b>: A small flat piece used in mosaics\n<b>Pattern</b>: A design that repeats shapes or colours\n<b>Adhesive</b>: A substance used to stick things together\n<b>Colour Harmony</b>: A pleasing arrangement of colours', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:38:18'),
(60, 4, 5, 'Lesson 6', '', 'Big Question: How can we decorate calabash and wood to reflect our culture?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Identify traditional motifs used in calabash and wood decoration.\n2. Learn painting and carving techniques.\n3. Apply designs to a small calabash or wooden object.\n4. Reflect on how decoration conveys cultural stories and values.', '<b>Decoration</b>: The act of making something look more attractive\n<b>Motif</b>: A repeated design or symbol often used in traditional art\n<b>Calabash</b>: A gourd used for containers or decoration\n<b>Carving</b>: Cutting into a material to form shapes or designs\n<b>Paint</b>: A coloured substance used to create artwork', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:38:18'),
(61, 4, 5, 'Lesson 7', '', '', '<b>Music</b>: A form of art made by combining sounds\n<b>Sound</b>: Vibrations that travel through the air and can be heard\n<b>Beat</b>: A steady pulse in music\n<b>Melody</b>: A series of musical notes that make a tune\n<b>Rhythm</b>: A pattern of beats or sounds', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:38:18'),
(62, 4, 5, 'Lesson 8', '', '', '<b>Identity</b>: What makes someone or something unique\n<b>National Identity</b>: A sense of belonging to a country\n<b>Value</b>: Something important or meaningful\n<b>Cultural Song</b>: A song that reflects the customs and beliefs of a people\n<b>Patriotism</b>: Love and loyalty to ones country', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:38:18'),
(63, 4, 5, 'Lesson 9', '', '', '<b>Drama</b>: A story performed by actors on stage\n<b>Performance</b>: The act of presenting a play or drama\n<b>Role</b>: The part an actor plays in a drama\n<b>Improvisation</b>: Making up dialogue or action without a script\n<b>Dialogue</b>: The spoken words between characters', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:38:18'),
(64, 4, 5, 'Lesson 10', '', '', '<b>Costume</b>: Special clothing worn to represent a character or culture\n<b>Mask</b>: A covering worn on the face to represent someone or something\n<b>Prop</b>: An object used by actors during a performance\n<b>Symbolism</b>: Using objects or actions to represent ideas\n<b>Traditional</b>: Based on customs and beliefs passed down through generations', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:38:18'),
(65, 4, 5, 'Lesson 11', '', '', '<b>Design</b>: A plan for how something should look or work\n<b>Shape</b>: The outline of an object\n<b>Colour</b>: A quality such as red, blue, or green\n<b>Texture</b>: How a surface feels or appears to feel\n<b>Balance</b>: The even arrangement of elements in design', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:38:18'),
(66, 4, 5, 'Lesson 12', '', '', '<b>Art Exhibition</b>: An event where artworks are displayed to the public\n<b>Gallery</b>: A place where art is shown\n<b>Audience</b>: People who view or listen to a performance or display\n<b>Critique</b>: To review or give feedback on a work of art\n<b>Presentation</b>: Showing something for others to see or experience', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:38:18'),
(67, 4, 5, 'Lesson 13', '', '', NULL, '', '', '', '2025-05-04 11:11:18'),
(68, 8, 5, 'Lesson 2', '', '', '<b>Family Resources</b>: Things that a family uses to meet their needs (time, money, energy, etc.)\n<b>Time</b>: The period during which tasks are done\n<b>Energy</b>: Strength and effort used to do work\n<b>Money</b>: Used to buy things and pay for services\n<b>Skill</b>: The ability to do something well', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:40:10'),
(69, 8, 5, 'Lesson 3', '', '', '<b>Saving</b>: Keeping money for future use\n<b>Bank</b>: A place where people keep their money safely\n<b>Piggy Bank</b>: A container used to store coins and savings at home\n<b>Goal</b>: Something you aim to achieve\n<b>Discipline</b>: The ability to control your actions and stick to a plan', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:40:10'),
(70, 8, 5, 'Lesson 4', '', '', '<b>Clothing</b>: What people wear to cover their body\n<b>Comfort</b>: A state of physical ease\n<b>Occasion</b>: A special event or activity\n<b>Weather</b>: The condition of the atmosphere (hot, cold, rainy)\n<b>Style</b>: A particular design or way of wearing clothes', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:40:10'),
(71, 8, 5, 'Lesson 5', '', '', '<b>Clothing Care</b>: The ways we keep clothes clean and in good shape\n<b>Washing</b>: Cleaning clothes using water and soap\n<b>Ironing</b>: Removing wrinkles from clothes using heat\n<b>Storage</b>: A place where clothes are kept when not being worn\n<b>Repairs</b>: Fixing damaged clothes', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:40:10'),
(72, 8, 5, 'Lesson 6', '', '', '<b>Food</b>: What we eat to grow and stay healthy\n<b>Nutrients</b>: Substances in food that help our body work properly\n<b>Balanced Diet</b>: A meal that contains all the food groups in the right amounts\n<b>Meal Plan</b>: A schedule of what to eat and when\n<b>Portion</b>: The amount of food served at one time', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:40:10'),
(73, 8, 5, 'Lesson 7', '', '', '<b>Food Safety</b>: Keeping food safe to eat and free from harm\n<b>Preservation</b>: Storing food so it lasts longer\n<b>Contamination</b>: When harmful things get into food\n<b>Cleanliness</b>: Being clean and keeping things clean\n<b>Hygiene</b>: Practices that keep us and our food healthy', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:40:10'),
(74, 8, 5, 'Lesson 8', '', '', '<b>Grooming</b>: Taking care of the body to look neat and clean\n<b>Appearance</b>: How someone looks\n<b>Personal Hygiene</b>: Keeping the body clean to stay healthy\n<b>Self-Esteem</b>: Feeling good about yourself\n<b>Confidence</b>: Believing in your abilities', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:40:10'),
(75, 6, 5, 'Lesson 13', '', 'Big Question: How do traditional occupations differ across Nigerias major ethnic groups?\n\nLearning Objectives:\n1. Identify and describe traditional occupations of the Hausa, Yoruba, and Igbo ethnic groups.\n2. Compare and contrast these occupations across the three groups.\n3. Understand modern changes impact on these trades.', '<b>Occupation</b>: A job or profession\n<b>Traditional Occupation</b>: Jobs that have been passed down in a community for generations\n<b>Farming</b>: Growing crops or raising animals\n<b>Fishing</b>: Catching fish for food or trade\n<b>Trading</b>: Buying and selling goods', '', '', '', '2025-05-25 22:39:23'),
(76, 17, 4, 'Lesson 1', 'Discovering Nigeria\'s Four Early Regions', 'Big Question: What is history and why do we learn it?\n\n\r\nLearning Objectives:\n\r\n1. Define history and its importance.\n\r\n2. Identify sources of history (oral, written, archaeological).\n\r\n3. Understand how studying the past helps us make better decisions today.\n\r\n4. Share personal or community stories as historical sources.', '<b>History</b>: The study of past events\n<b>Timeline</b>: A list of events in the order they happened\n<b>Tradition</b>: A belief or activity passed down over time\n<b>Oral History</b>: Stories and facts shared by word of mouth\n<b>Artifacts</b>: Objects made or used by people in the past', '', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cj5FhYPNCno', '2025-05-25 22:29:59'),
